00:35:52.267 --> 00:35:57.167
Venus has a massive
CO2 atmosphere.

00:35:57.167 --> 00:36:01.833
It is entirely covered
by clouds.

00:36:01.833 --> 00:36:05.433
100% cloud cover all the
time, which makes it

00:36:05.433 --> 00:36:08.300
a very bright planet.

00:36:08.300 --> 00:36:14.300
In fact, do you know the
colloquial term for Venus

00:36:14.300 --> 00:36:16.733
among astronomers, or
farmers, or sailors?

00:36:16.733 --> 00:36:19.233
STUDENT: Do they call it
the greenhouse planet?

00:36:19.233 --> 00:36:22.300
PROFESSOR: No, not colloquially.

00:36:22.300 --> 00:36:23.100
The evening star.

00:36:23.100 --> 00:36:24.200
It's called the evening star.

00:36:24.200 --> 00:36:25.467
That's an odd name, isn't it?

00:36:25.467 --> 00:36:28.267
Because it's not
a star at all.

00:36:28.267 --> 00:36:32.000
But when the sun sets in the
evening and the sky darkens,

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:34.867
that's usually the first
thing you can see.

00:36:34.867 --> 00:36:36.633
So the evening star,
they call it.

00:36:36.633 --> 00:36:37.200
Why is it?

00:36:37.200 --> 00:36:40.400
Because it's--well it's
relatively large, relatively

00:36:40.400 --> 00:36:42.467
close, but it's very bright.

00:36:42.467 --> 00:36:45.567
It reflects--it's completely
covered with white clouds,

00:36:45.567 --> 00:36:47.900
reflects a lot of sunlight,
and makes it

00:36:47.900 --> 00:36:49.167
easy for us to see.

00:36:52.233 --> 00:36:55.400
It turns out, though,
that it also has a

00:36:55.400 --> 00:36:57.433
super greenhouse effect.

00:36:57.433 --> 00:37:04.333
And it's a little bit closer
to the sun than we are, but

00:37:04.333 --> 00:37:08.267
its temperature is even hotter
than you would expect based on

00:37:08.267 --> 00:37:11.467
that proximity to the sun.

00:37:11.467 --> 00:37:13.967
It has a really super greenhouse
effect that brings

00:37:13.967 --> 00:37:19.733
it up to a temperature that's
in the order of 600 Celsius,

00:37:19.733 --> 00:37:21.667
way, way, way above the
boiling point and

00:37:21.667 --> 00:37:22.800
so on and so forth.

00:37:22.800 --> 00:37:25.400
So a very hot planet because
of the greenhouse effect.

00:37:25.400 --> 00:37:26.500
The Earth we know has a

00:37:26.500 --> 00:37:28.633
nitrogen-oxygen atmosphere primarily.

00:37:28.633 --> 00:37:30.200
Partly cloudy.

00:37:30.200 --> 00:37:32.000
Water can exist in
the liquid form.

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:33.967
We have life, and we
have ice caps.

00:37:33.967 --> 00:37:38.400
We have frozen water, in this
case in the form of snow or

00:37:38.400 --> 00:37:44.467
frozen seawater, at the caps,
at the poles of the planet.

00:37:44.467 --> 00:37:48.967
Mars has a CO2 atmosphere
but not much of it.

00:37:51.667 --> 00:37:53.567
There may have been
water there once.

00:37:53.567 --> 00:37:55.467
We don't know if it's
still there now.

00:37:55.467 --> 00:37:56.667
There may have been
life there once.

00:37:56.667 --> 00:37:58.133
We don't think it's there now.

00:37:58.133 --> 00:37:59.567
But it too has some ice caps.

00:37:59.567 --> 00:38:02.667
If you look at the planet, it
has these kind of snowy

00:38:02.667 --> 00:38:05.033
regions near the poles.

00:38:05.033 --> 00:38:06.733
We don't think it's
frozen water.

00:38:06.733 --> 00:38:09.067
We think it's frozen C02.

00:38:09.067 --> 00:38:12.133
What's frozen CO2 called?

00:38:12.133 --> 00:38:12.967
Dry ice.

00:38:12.967 --> 00:38:18.033
Dry ice is what we
call frozen CO2.

00:38:18.033 --> 00:38:23.000
Mars seems to have dry ice ice
caps on the poles that change

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:25.700
a bit with the season.

00:38:25.700 --> 00:38:27.333
So the point here--

00:38:27.333 --> 00:38:29.133
we're not going to be studying,
